{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493179"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:59:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1245"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1245"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.5,0.16,0.14,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1245"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"23116"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1245"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1245"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11594"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"679"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2035"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"23116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/23116"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of sudden onset of severe pain in his right leg. His medical history includes atrial fibrillation, for which he takes apixaban. On examination his blood pressure is 142/84 mmHg and an irregular pulse 100/min. The right leg is pale, cool and no pulses can be felt below the femoral pulse. A CT angiogram show an obstruction at the femoro-popliteal junction. He is diagnosed with a Rutherford class IIa acute limb ischaemia. A heparin infusion is started.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Balloon angioplasty","Catheter-directed thrombolysis","Endarterectomy","Femoro-popliteal bypass","Femoro-tibial bypass"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with acute limb ischaemia most likely due to a cardiac embolism because of atrial fibrillation requires rapid revascularisation to prevent further ischaemic damage to his limb. The management of acute limb ischaemia depends on a number of factors (eg, the extent of obstruction, Rutherford class, aetiology, etc). This patient with an embolic aetiology and Rutherford class IIa will most likely benefit from \u003Cstrong\u003Ecatheter-directed thrombolysis \u003C/strong\u003Ewith or without thrombectomy. Bypass procedures might be preferred for thrombotic situations, but in this case with embolism, a catheter-directed line of approach should be considered first. Of course this will depend on the availability of an interventional radiologist. Input from haematology will be important, as the anticoagulation with apixaban will make the risk of intraprocedural bleeding high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBalloon angioplasty and endarterectomy are considered approaches for limb ischaemia caused by a thrombotic phenomenon.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thrombolysis is the preferred approach for acute femoral artery embolism."],"references":["Bjorck M, Earnshaw JJ, Acosta S et al. European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) 2020 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Acute Limb Ischaemia. Our J Endovasc Surg 2020; 59:173-18."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11594"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1245"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11594"